dataExt.exDesc: This feature class identifies critical facilities along the Oregon coast as shown on tsunami evacuation brochures and tsunami inundation maps.

dataIdInfo.idPurp:
The intent of this digital data release is to provide seamless, statewide tsunami inundation scenarios in the form of ArcGIS shapefiles for seven scenarios selected for depiction on published Oregon Department of Geology and Mineral Industries (DOGAMI) tsunami inundation maps (TIMâ€™s). These scenarios include five from local Cascadia subduction zone (CSZ) earthquakes (SM1, M1, L1, XL1, and XXL1), and two maximum-considered distant tsunamis from subduction zone earthquakes in the Gulf of Alaska: a historical maximum that occurred in 1964 (AK64) and a hypothetical maximum (AKMax) with higher uplift and more efficient focusing of tsunami energy at the Oregon coast than in 1964.
Also included in this publication are supplemental files that support the tsunami model data publications, tsunami evacuation brochures, education and outreach initiatives, and other tsunami related publications (ex. TIM's).
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This shapefile is a supplemental file to the primary tsunami inundation scenarios released with this publication. The critical facility locations depicted in this shapefile are those shown on the tsunami evacuation brochures and on the TIM's which can be found on the Oregon Tsunami Clearinghouse web site: www.oregontsunami.org,

The features represented are: public school, hospital, airport, fire station, police station, city hall, bridge, sheriff office, and tsunami siren.

dataLineage.statement: The features within this shapefile were collected from many meetings occuring from 2011-2013. Tsunami evacuation brochures were created and reviewed with local representatives for the most populated communities along the Oregon coast. This feature class is a digital representation of the critical facility locations shown on these maps.

prcStep.stepDesc: This data layer was created through map review meetings conducted at each community where these facilities were identified by local government representatives and local emergency responders. The points were then added to a shapefile using heads-up digitizing from aerial photos and other reference GIS data layers in ArcGIS.
